It is true that a difficulty is introduced by the fact that Mutiarr-a-lso saw in 1514 a ‘⁶ Triumph of Reuchlin'' by ‘⁶ Accius Neobius‚’' and this he attributes to Hermann von dem Busche. There can be little doubt that the two documents were drafts of one and the same poem (the change of pseudonym is clearly unimportant)‚ and it is of course by no means improbable that Buschius as well as Hutten had a hand in it. In the twenty-fifth letter of the first series of the Epistolae it is plainly stated that ‘⁶ unus (poeta) jam composuit unum librum qui vocatur Triumphus Capnionis, et continet multa scandala de vobis.'' It is to be observed that the poem is here merely spoken of as “composed‚'’ not printed or pub- lished, and, as we have seen, it did not appear until three years later. The somewhat tangled chain of cir- cumstances connected with the Triumphus at any rate tends to illustrate the fact that the German humanists of the day kept in touch with one another on the sub- ject of the great controversy which so keenly interested them, and that their manuscripts were freely handed about, whether for criticism or mutual admiration.
